MONGODB vs SQL:
  SQL: tables, rows, columns, schema-strict
  MongoDB: collections, documents (JSON/BSON), schema-flexible

WHEN TO USE MONGODB:
• Variable or evolving schema (different documents in same collection)
• Hierarchical/nested data (no joins needed)
• High write throughput
• Storing JSON from REST APIs directly

DOCUMENT MODEL:
  // MongoDB document (BSON — Binary JSON)
  {
    _id: ObjectId("64abc123..."),  // auto-generated unique ID
    name: "Alice",
    age: 28,
    address: {
      city: "Chennai",
      pincode: "600001"
    },
    skills: ["Java", "Spring", "MongoDB"],
    createdAt: ISODate("2024-01-15")
  }

DATA TYPES: String, Number, Boolean, Date, ObjectId, Array, Object, Null, Binary

CRUD IN MONGODB:
  // Insert
  db.users.insertOne({ name: "Bob", age: 30 });
  db.users.insertMany([{ name: "Alice" }, { name: "Charlie" }]);

  // Find
  db.users.find();                           // all documents
  db.users.findOne({ name: "Alice" });       // first match
  db.users.find({ age: { $gt: 25 } });       // age > 25
  db.users.find({ city: "Chennai" }, { name: 1, _id: 0 }); // projection

  // Update
  db.users.updateOne({ name: "Alice" }, { $set: { age: 29 } });
  db.users.updateMany({ dept: "IT" }, { $inc: { salary: 5000 } });

  // Delete
  db.users.deleteOne({ name: "Bob" });
  db.users.deleteMany({ age: { $lt: 18 } });

  // Sort & Limit
  db.users.find().sort({ age: -1 }).limit(5).skip(10);

QUERY OPERATORS:
  Comparison: $eq, $ne, $gt, $gte, $lt, $lte
  Array: $in, $nin, $all, $elemMatch
  Logical: $and, $or, $not, $nor
  Field: $exists, $type

AGGREGATION PIPELINE:
  db.orders.aggregate([
    { $match: { status: "completed" } },
    { $group: { _id: "$customerId", total: { $sum: "$amount" } } },
    { $sort: { total: -1 } },
    { $limit: 10 }
  ]);

INDEXES:
  db.users.createIndex({ name: 1 });        // ascending
  db.users.createIndex({ email: 1 }, { unique: true });
  db.collection.explain("executionStats"); // check if index is used

TRANSACTIONS (MongoDB 4.0+):
  session.startTransaction();
  // operations
  session.commitTransaction();

SPRING DATA MONGODB:
  @Document(collection = "users")
  public class User { @Id String id; String name; }

  public interface UserRepo extends MongoRepository<User, String> {
    List<User> findByCity(String city);
  }

SCHEMA DESIGN PATTERNS:
  Embedded: nest related data in one document (avoid joins)
  Referenced: store ObjectId and use $lookup (like SQL JOIN)
  Bucket Pattern: group time-series data into buckets
  Anti-patterns: unbounded arrays, over-embedding, using as SQL replacement

